<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="235" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,537,780]" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,681,707]" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Remarks.</emphasis>
Distributed in the Azores, 
<collectingRegion box="[635,809,681,707]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Canary Islands</collectingRegion>
, and from 
<collectingCountry box="[940,1004,681,707]" name="Spain" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Spain</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1129,681,707]" name="Greece" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Greece</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1143,1223,681,707]" name="Turkey" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Turkey</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1285,1347,681,707]" name="Israel" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Israel</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="World Spider Catalog" pageId="7" pageNumber="235" refId="ref14500" refString="World Spider Catalog (2021) World Spider Catalog. Version 21.5. Natural History Museum Bern. Available from: http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (accessed 28 February 2021) https: // doi. org / 10.24436 / 2" type="book" year="2021">World Spider Catalog 2021</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[631,727,717,743]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
fits well with the original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Simon, E." box="[1193,1348,717,743]" pageId="7" pageNumber="235" pagination="1 - 308" refId="ref14183" refString="Simon, E. (1914) Les arachnides de France. Synopsis generale et catalogue des especes francaises de l'ordre des Araneae. Tome VI. 1 re partie. Roret, Paris, pp. 1 - 308." type="book chapter" year="1914">Simon (1914)</bibRefCitation>
and we provide new photographs of the male habitus (
<figureCitation box="[672,760,753,780]" captionStart="FIGURES 6" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1430,1454]" captionTargetBox="[256,1323,811,1395]" captionTargetId="figure-192@7.[248,1339,803,1407]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 6A–C. Leptodrassus albidus, male. A Habitus, dorsal. B–C Left palp (B ventral, C retrolateral). C—conductor, Em—embolus, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4927042" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4927042/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
) and palp (
<figureCitation box="[885,1009,753,780]" captionStart="FIGURES 6" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1430,1454]" captionTargetBox="[256,1323,811,1395]" captionTargetId="figure-192@7.[248,1339,803,1407]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 6A–C. Leptodrassus albidus, male. A Habitus, dorsal. B–C Left palp (B ventral, C retrolateral). C—conductor, Em—embolus, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4927042" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4927042/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="235">Figs 6B–C</figureCitation>
) for comparison.
</paragraph>
